16. A method to implement a biased probabilistic sampler process to select new batches of unlabeled instances, comprising:
by one or more computing devices:
obtaining a current version of a classification model M, an unlabeled set of available documents D, and a cosine similarity threshold t;
constructing a weight vector w based on an inverse operation of a distance from the current version of the classification model M for each document from the unlabeled set of available documents D;
normalizing the weight vector w for each document to convert the weight vector w into a probability vector;
choosing a document I[1] from the unlabeled set of available documents D using the corresponding probability vector;
inserting the chosen document I[1] into a new batch of unlabeled instances Bc;
identifying documents of the remaining unlabeled set of available documents D that have a cosine similarity angle ≥t with respect to the chosen document I[1];
removing the identified documents from the unlabeled set of available documents D;
re-normalizing the weight vector w for each remaining document in the set of documents D; and
repeating the choose operation, the insert operation, the identify operation, the remove operation, and the re-normalize operation until the new batch of unlabeled instances Bc are selected.
17. The method of claim 16, wherein, in the obtaining step, the one or more computing devices further obtains a batch size k.
18. The method of claim 17, wherein the one or more computing devises performs the steps of repeating the choose operation, the insert operation, the identify operation, the remove operation, and the re-normalize operation until k documents are inserted into the new batch of unlabeled instances Bc.
19. The method of claim 16, wherein the current version of the classification model M is created by:
obtaining an unlabeled set of documents D;
